com.smartsockets
Interface TipcMt

All Superinterfaces:
TipcDefs
public interface TipcMt
extends TipcDefs

Provides access to the message type class.

This interface is used by TipcMt objects returned from the TipcSvc factory class to create user-defined message types and to lookup both user-defined message types and standard SmartSockets message types.

This interface also contains the identifiers for the standard SmartSockets message types.

Note: All user-defined message type numbers must be greater than zero. All SmartSockets-defined message type numbers are less than zero. Zero is not a valid message type number.

See Also:
TipcMsg, TipcSvc

getDeliveryMode

public int getDeliveryMode()
Gets the delivery mode for the message type. The delivery mode of a message type is used as the default delivery mode for messages of this type. When a message is created, its delivery mode is initialized to the message type delivery mode.

The default message type delivery mode is TipcDefs.DELIVERY_BEST_EFFORT. The other delivery modes are TipcDefs.DELIVERY_ORDERED, TipcDefs.DELIVERY_SOME and TipcDefs.DELIVERY_ALL.

The delivery mode of an outgoing message can always be set on a per-message basis, but using message type delivery modes makes it easier to change the default delivery mode for all outgoing messages of a specific type. The standard SmartSockets message types by default all have a delivery mode of TipcDefs.DELIVERY_BEST_EFFORT, but these can be changed. User-defined message types can also use whatever delivery mode is appropriate.

Returns:
The delivery mode of the message type.
See Also:
setDeliveryMode(int), TipcMsg.setDeliveryMode(int), TipcMsg.getDeliveryMode()

getPriority

public short getPriority()
Gets the priority of the message type. The priority of a message type, if set, is used as the default priority for messages of this type. The message type priority can either be set to a specific value or it can be unknown. When a message is created, its priority is initialized to the message type priority (if set) or to the value of the option ss.default_msg_priority (if the message type priority is unknown).

The priority of an outgoing message can always be set on a per-message basis, but using message type priorities makes it easier to raise or lower the default priority for all outgoing messages of a specific type. The standard SmartSockets message types by default all have a priority of unknown, but these can be changed. User-defined message types can also use whatever priority is appropriate.

Returns:
The message type priority.
See Also:
setPriority(short), setPriorityUnknown(), TipcMsg.setPriority(short), TipcMsg.getPriority()

getLbMode

public int getLbMode()
Gets the load balancing mode for the message type. The load balancing mode of a message controls how (or if) the message is load balanced among RTclients subscribed to a load balanced subject. The load balancing mode of a message type is used as the default load balancing mode for messages of this type. When a message is created, its load balancing mode is initialized to the message type load balancing mode.

The default message type load balancing mode is TipcDefs.LB_NONE. The other load balancing modes are TipcDefs.LB_ROUND_ROBIN, TipcDefs.LB_WEIGHTED, and TipcDefs.LB_SORTED.

The load balancing mode of an outgoing message can always be set on a per-message basis, but using message type load balancing modes makes it easier to change the default load balancing mode for all outgoing messages of a specific type. The standard SmartSockets message types by default all have a load balancing mode of TipcDefs.LB_NONE, but these can be changed. User-defined message types can also use whatever load balancing mode is appropriate.

Returns:
The load balancing mode of the message type.
